<DOC><DOCNO> AP890627-0168 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 2051EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     06-27 0250</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Salvador,0257</SECOND><HEAD>Guerrillas Say They Killed Colonel</HEAD><DATELINE>SAN SALVADR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Leftist rebels Tuesday tookresponsiblity for the assassination of an army colonel and said heparticipated in rightist death squads.   Col. Roberto Rivera, director of the National Firemen's Corpssince June 1, was slain Monday as he drove to work.   He was previously director of the Public Security Academy andassistant director of Treasury Police.   ``Col. Rivera was a military man with a criminal and repressivetrajectory,'' said a rebel communique broadcast on the clandestineRadio Venceremos. ``His activity was clearly linked to deathsquads.''   A nine-year civil war between the Farabundo Marti NationalLiberation Front, known as FMLN, and the U.S.-backed government hasleft an estimated 70,000 people dead. Human rights groups say morethan 20,000 people were killed by military-linked rightist deathsquads in the early 1980s.   ``The FMLN reiterates that the `dirty war' actions of thegovernment against civilans will receive a firm response from thepeople in arms,'' said the rebel communique.   In Washington, the State Department on Tuesday renewed its appealto the rebels to negotiate with the government on ending the civilwar in a statement prompted by Monday's slaying.   Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler noted that SalvadoranPresident Alfredo Cristiani has formed a national commission to talkto the guerrilla movement.   ``We repeat our call to the FMLN to end the violence in ElSalvador and to enter into negotiations without preconditions aimedat ending the conflict,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.</TEXT></DOC>